Step 1: Dataset Summary & Exploration¶

The pickled data is a dictionary with 4 key/value pairs:

  • 'features' is a 4D array containing raw pixel data of the traffic sign images, (num examples, width, height, channels).
  • 'labels' is a 1D array containing the label/class id of the traffic sign. The file signnames.csv contains id -> name mappings for each id.
  • 'sizes' is a list containing tuples, (width, height) representing the original width and height the image.
  • 'coords' is a list containing tuples, (x1, y1, x2, y2) representing coordinates of a bounding box around the sign in the image. THESE COORDINATES ASSUME THE ORIGINAL IMAGE. THE PICKLED DATA CONTAINS RESIZED VERSIONS (32 by 32) OF THESE IMAGES

def display_DataSample(dataSet, labels):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 20))  
    for i in range(9): 
        index = random.randint(0, len(dataSet))
        image = dataSet[index].squeeze()
        
        sub = fig.add_subplot(1, 9, i+1)
        sub.imshow(image, interpolation='nearest')
        plt.title(signnames.loc[labels[index],"SignName"])
       
    return

Step 2: Design and Test a Model Architecture¶

Design and implement a deep learning model that learns to recognize traffic signs. Train and test your model on the German Traffic Sign Dataset.

The LeNet-5 implementation shown in the classroom at the end of the CNN lesson is a solid starting point. You'll have to change the number of classes and possibly the preprocessing, but aside from that it's plug and play!

With the LeNet-5 solution from the lecture, you should expect a validation set accuracy of about 0.89. To meet specifications, the validation set accuracy will need to be at least 0.93. It is possible to get an even higher accuracy, but 0.93 is the minimum for a successful project submission.

There are various aspects to consider when thinking about this problem:

  • Neural network architecture (is the network over or underfitting?)
  • Play around preprocessing techniques (normalization, rgb to grayscale, etc)
  • Number of examples per label (some have more than others).
  • Generate fake data.

Here is an example of a published baseline model on this problem. It's not required to be familiar with the approach used in the paper but, it's good practice to try to read papers like these.

Pre-process the Data Set (normalization, grayscale, etc.)¶

Minimally, the image data should be normalized so that the data has mean zero and equal variance. For image data, (pixel - 128)/ 128 is a quick way to approximately normalize the data and can be used in this project.

Other pre-processing steps are optional. You can try different techniques to see if it improves performance.

Use the code cell (or multiple code cells, if necessary) to implement the first step of your project.

The following Data preproccessing steps are performed:¶

1- Converting the images to the grayscale as this helps in increasing the accuracy. 2- Data Normalization. 3- Histogram equalization. 4- Data shuffling.

Note that: I've looked for the most vital preprocessing steps fro the traffic signs data sets and I selected the mentioned steps then, but there're lot of other steps left for ex. Data Augmentation (Flipping, rotation,..etc), but these steps sufficed the project requirements.

In [27]:
from sklearn import preprocessing
from sklearn.utils import shuffle
from skimage import exposure
import cv2

### Preprocess the data here. It is required to normalize the data. Other preprocessing steps could include 

def preprocess_dataset(X, y = None):
    
    # 1- Convert to grayscale, e.g. single Y channel
    X_trainGray = 0.299 * X[:, :, :, 0] + 0.587 * X[:, :, :, 1] + 0.114 * X[:, :, :, 2]
    
    # 2- Scale features to be in [0, 1]
    X_trainNorm = (X_trainGray / 255.).astype(np.float32)
      
    # 3- Apply localized histogram localization
    X_trainHistEq = np.zeros_like(X_trainNorm)
    for i in range(X_trainNorm.shape[0]):
        X_trainHistEq[i] = exposure.equalize_adapthist(X_trainNorm[i])
        
    if y is not None:  
         
        # 4-  Shuffle the data
        X_shuffle, y_shuffle = shuffle(X_trainHistEq, y)

    # Add a single grayscale channel
    X_trainPrep = X_shuffle.reshape(X_shuffle.shape + (1,)) 
    y_trainPrep = y_shuffle
    
    
    return X_trainPrep, y_trainPrep

Two Different Models Are Trained (1- LeNet Model 2- VGGNet Model)¶

  • When I walked through this project actually I trained Lenet firstly with different selections of the hyperparameters (Batch size, Epochs No, Learning rate) and I wrote the resulted accuracies until I got the highest accuracy value then I saved LeNet model.

  • The same procedure was performed on AlexNet and VGGNet models but actually I'm viewing here just two models of them which are LeNet and VGGNet models which gave me the best accuarcies for the validation accuracy as shown below.

  • In order to improve these models performance on the test set I used a dropout layer on each of them with a probability of 0.5.

LeNet Architecture¶

In [33]:
### LeNet Architecture
import tensorflow as tf



### Feel free to use as many code cells as needed.

from tensorflow.contrib.layers import flatten

def LeNet(x):    
    # Arguments used for tf.truncated_normal, randomly defines variables for the weights and biases for each layer
    mu = 0
    sigma = 0.1
    
    # Layer 1: Convolutional. Input = 32x32x1. Output = 28x28x6.
    conv1_W = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(5, 5, 1, 6), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    conv1_b = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(6))
    conv1   = tf.nn.conv2d(x, conv1_W, strides=[1, 1, 1, 1], padding='VALID') + conv1_b

    #  Activation.
    conv1 = tf.nn.relu(conv1)

    # Dropout Layer
    conv1_drpout = tf.layers.dropout(conv1, 0.5)
    
    #  Pooling1 . Input = 28x28x6. Output = 14x14x6.
    pool1 = tf.nn.max_pool(conv1_drpout, ksize=[1, 2, 2, 1], strides=[1, 2, 2, 1], padding='VALID')

    #  Layer 2: Convolutional.Input = 14x14x6. Output = 10x10x16.
    conv2_W = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(5, 5, 6, 16), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    conv2_b = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(16))
    conv2   = tf.nn.conv2d(pool1, conv2_W, strides=[1, 1, 1, 1], padding='VALID') + conv2_b
    
    #  Activation.
    conv2 = tf.nn.relu(conv2)

    
    #  Layer 2': Convolutional.Input = 10x10x16. Output = 10x10x16.
    #conv3_W = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(10, 10, 16, 16), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    #conv3_b = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(16))
    #conv3   = tf.nn.conv2d(conv2, conv3_W, strides=[1, 1, 1, 1], padding='SAME') + conv3_b
       
    # Activation.
    #conv3 = tf.nn.relu(conv3)
    
    # Pooling2 . Input = 10x10x16. Output = 5x5x16.
    pool2 = tf.nn.max_pool(conv2, ksize=[1, 2, 2, 1], strides=[1, 2, 2, 1], padding='VALID')

    #  Flatten. Input = 5x5x16. Output = 400.
    fc0   = flatten(pool2)
    
    #  Layer 3: Fully Connected. Input = 400. Output = 120.
    fc1_W = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(400, 120), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    fc1_b = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(120))
    fc1   = tf.matmul(fc0, fc1_W) + fc1_b
    
    #  Activation.
    fc1    = tf.nn.relu(fc1)

    #  Layer 4: Fully Connected. Input = 120. Output = 84.
    fc2_W  = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(120, 84), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    fc2_b  = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(84))
    fc2    = tf.matmul(fc1, fc2_W) + fc2_b
    
    #  Activation.
    fc2    = tf.nn.relu(fc2)

    #  Layer 5: Fully Connected. Input = 84. Output = 10.
    fc3_W  = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(84, 43), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    fc3_b  = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(43))
    logits = tf.matmul(fc2, fc3_W) + fc3_b
    
    return logits

VGGNet Architecture¶

In [34]:
## VGGNet Architecture

import tensorflow as tf


from tensorflow.contrib.layers import flatten

def VGGNet16(x):
    
    # Arguments used for tf.truncated_normal, randomly defines variables for the weights and biases for each layer
    mu = 0
    sigma = 0.1
    
    # Layer 1: Convolutional. Input = 32x32x1. Output = 30x30x64.
    conv1_W = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(3, 3, 1, 64), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    conv1_b = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(64))
    conv1   = tf.nn.conv2d(x, conv1_W, strides=[1, 1, 1, 1], padding='VALID') + conv1_b

    #  Activation.
    conv1 = tf.nn.relu(conv1)
    
    #Droupout Layer
    conv1_drpout = tf.nn.dropout(conv1, 0.5)
    
    #print(conv1.get_shape())
    #  Layer 2: Convolutional. Input = 30x30x64 . Output = 28x28x64.
    conv2_W = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(3, 3, 64, 64), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    conv2_b = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(64))
    conv2   = tf.nn.conv2d(conv1_drpout, conv2_W, strides=[1, 1, 1, 1], padding='VALID') + conv2_b

    #  Activation.
    conv2 = tf.nn.relu(conv2)

    #print(conv2.get_shape())
    #  Pooling1. Input = 28x28x64. Output = 14x14x64.
    pool1 = tf.nn.max_pool(conv2, ksize=[1, 2, 2, 1], strides=[1, 2, 2, 1], padding='VALID')

    #print(pool1.get_shape())
    # Layer 3: Convolutional. Input = 14x14x64. Output = 12x12x128.
    conv3_W = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(3, 3, 64, 128), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    conv3_b = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(128))
    conv3   = tf.nn.conv2d(pool1, conv3_W, strides=[1, 1, 1, 1], padding='VALID') + conv3_b
    
    #  Activation.
    conv3 = tf.nn.relu(conv3)
    
    # Layer 4: Convolutional. Input = 12x12x128. Output = 10x10x128.
    conv4_W = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(3, 3, 128, 128), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    conv4_b = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(128))
    conv4   = tf.nn.conv2d(conv3, conv4_W, strides=[1, 1, 1, 1], padding='VALID') + conv4_b
    
    #  Activation.
    conv4 = tf.nn.relu(conv4)    
    
    #print(conv3.get_shape())
    #  Pooling2. Input = 10x10x128. Output = 5x5x128.
    pool2 = tf.nn.max_pool(conv4, ksize=[1, 2, 2, 1], strides=[1, 2, 2, 1], padding='VALID')
    
    
    #print(conv4.shape)
    #  Layer 5: Convolutional. Input = 5x5x128. Output = 3x3x256.
    conv5_W = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(3, 3, 128, 256), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    conv5_b = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(256))
    conv5   = tf.nn.conv2d(pool2, conv5_W, strides=[1, 1, 1, 1], padding='VALID') + conv5_b

    #  Activation.
    conv5 = tf.nn.relu(conv5)
    
    
    #print(conv4.shape)
    #  Layer 6: Convolutional. Input = 3x3x256. Output = 1x1x256.
    conv6_W = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(3, 3, 256, 256), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    conv6_b = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(256))
    conv6   = tf.nn.conv2d(conv5, conv6_W, strides=[1, 1, 1, 1], padding='VALID') + conv6_b

    #  Activation.
    conv6 = tf.nn.relu(conv6)

    #print(conv5.shape)
    #  Pooling3. Input = 1x1x256. Output = 1x1x256.
    #pool3 = tf.nn.max_pool(conv6, ksize=[1, 2, 2, 1], strides=[1, 2, 2, 1], padding='VALID')
    
    #print(pool3.shape)
    # SOLUTION: Flatten. Input = 1x1x256. Output = 256.
    fl0   = flatten(conv6)
    
    # SOLUTION: Layer 3: Fully Connected. Input = 256. Output = 4096.
    fc1_W = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(256, 4096), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    fc1_b = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(4096))
    fc1   = tf.matmul(fl0, fc1_W) + fc1_b
    
    # SOLUTION: Activation.
    fc1    = tf.nn.relu(fc1)

    # SOLUTION: Layer 4: Fully Connected. Input = 4096. Output = 4096.
    fc2_W  = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(4096, 4096), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    fc2_b  = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(4096))
    fc2    = tf.matmul(fc1, fc2_W) + fc2_b
    
    # SOLUTION: Activation.
    fc2    = tf.nn.relu(fc2)

    # SOLUTION: Layer 5: Fully Connected. Input = 4096. Output = 43.
    fc3_W  = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(4096, 43), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))
    fc3_b  = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(43))
    logits = tf.matmul(fc2, fc3_W) + fc3_b
    
    return logits

Train, Validate and Test the Model¶

A validation set can be used to assess how well the model is performing. A low accuracy on the training and validation sets imply underfitting. A high accuracy on the training set but low accuracy on the validation set implies overfitting.

Training & Optimization Walk-through¶

I've tried many combinations of the hyper parameters during the model tuning in order to get the model best performance on this data set. Here is summary of these combinations I've used for each model been trained:

1- LeNet Tuning:

2- VGGNet Tuning:

Also, I've trained AlexNet Model:

  • The Optimization algorithm used here is AdamOptimizer which is an extension to stochastic gradient descent.

  • AdamOptimizer is combining the advantages of two other extensions of stochastic gradient descent. Specifically:

  • Adaptive Gradient Algorithm (AdaGrad) that maintains a per-parameter learning rate that improves performance on problems with sparse gradients (e.g. natural language and computer vision problems).

  • Root Mean Square Propagation (RMSProp) that also maintains per-parameter learning rates that are adapted based on the average of recent magnitudes of the gradients for the weight (e.g. how quickly it is changing). This means the algorithm does well on online and non-stationary problems (e.g. noisy).

  • Adam was demonstrated empirically to show that convergence meets the expectations of the theoretical analysis. Adam was applied to the logistic regression algorithm on the MNIST character recognition and IMDB sentiment analysis datasets, a Multilayer Perceptron algorithm on the MNIST dataset and Convolutional Neural Networks on the CIFAR-10 image recognition dataset.

And here's Comparison of Adam to Other Optimization Algorithms Training a Multilayer Perceptron

  • Taken from Adam: A Method for Stochastic Optimization, 2015.

In [38]:
### LeNet Evaluation
correct_prediction_LeNet = tf.equal(tf.argmax(logits_LeNet, 1), tf.argmax(one_hot_y, 1))
accuracy_operation_LeNet = tf.reduce_mean(tf.cast(correct_prediction_LeNet, tf.float32))
saver = tf.train.Saver()

def evaluate_LeNet(X_data, y_data, BATCH_SIZE):
    num_examples = len(X_data)
    total_accuracy_LeNet = 0
    sess = tf.get_default_session()
    for offset in range(0, num_examples, BATCH_SIZE):
        batch_x, batch_y = X_data[offset:offset+BATCH_SIZE], y_data[offset:offset+BATCH_SIZE]
        accuracy_LeNet = sess.run(accuracy_operation_LeNet, feed_dict={x: batch_x, y: batch_y})
        total_accuracy_LeNet += (accuracy_LeNet * len(batch_x))
    return total_accuracy_LeNet / num_examples

### LeNet Training
BATCH_SIZE = 128
EPOCHS = 25
with tf.Session() as sess:
    sess.run(tf.global_variables_initializer())
    num_examples = len(X_train)
    
    print("Training...")
    print()
    for i in range(EPOCHS):
        X_train, y_train = shuffle(X_trainPrep, y_trainPrep)
        for offset in range(0, num_examples, BATCH_SIZE):
            end = offset + BATCH_SIZE
            batch_x, batch_y = X_trainPrep[offset:end], y_trainPrep[offset:end]
            sess.run(training_operation_LeNet, feed_dict={x: batch_x, y: batch_y})
            
        validation_accuracy = evaluate_LeNet(X_validPrep, y_validPrep, BATCH_SIZE)
        print("EPOCH {} ...".format(i+1))
        print("LeNet Validation Accuracy = {:.3f} %".format(validation_accuracy*100))
        print()
        
    saver.save(sess, './lenet')
    print("Model saved")

Step 3: Test a Model on New Images¶

To give yourself more insight into how your model is working, download at least five pictures of German traffic signs from the web and use your model to predict the traffic sign type.

You may find signnames.csv useful as it contains mappings from the class id (integer) to the actual sign name.

Load and Output the Images¶

  • Five different images from German traffic signs are used here with their labels as a test set for our two models taken into consideration the followings:

    1- Traffic sign should be in the center of the image (i.e Our models are not trained to recognize the traffic sign if the

      image contains many different objects, models can only classify the sign, so the image should only contain the traffic 
  sign centered in it).

    2- No restrictions on the image size as the pipeline will care about resizing step to assure that the input image to the preprocessing setp will be (32, 32, 3).

In [56]:
def display_ExtraSample(dataSet, labels):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 20))  
    for i in range(len(dataSet)): 
        #index = random.randint(0, (len(dataSet) - 1))
        image = dataSet[i].squeeze()
        
        sub = fig.add_subplot(1, 5, i+1)
        sub.imshow(image, interpolation='nearest')
        plt.title(signnames.loc[labels[i],"SignName"])
       
    return

def img_resize(img):
    
    resized_img = cv2.resize(img, (32,32))
    return resized_img

## Resizing step

xT_resizedlist = list(map(img_resize, xT))

Conclusion¶

  • As we observe that LeNet & VGGNet models don't perform well in classifying the following classes:

1- Stop Class - Class ID 14. 2- Pedestrians Class - Class ID 27. 3- Speed Limit (60 KM/Hr) - Class ID 3.

  • And this is because these classes representations in the training set is relatively low as shown in the data visualization section above, hence the models are not trained enough to classify such classes.
  • Also another observation:

Even though VGGNet model failed to classify Pedestrian and Speed Limit-60 signs but it was certain in his worng classification unlike to the LeNet Model which was uncertain in the wrong classifications, I believe that this reflects each model (Precision & Accuracy) so we can roughly say that:

  • VGGNet Model is more precise than LeNet Model (More Certain in the classification even in the wrong ones).
  • LeNet Model is more accurate than VGGNet Model (Has more accuracy in the classification).

Supposed Future Improvements¶

I believe that the following enhancements could noticeablly improve these two models performance:

1- More data preprocessing (Data augmentation (for example: 1- Images Flipping))

In order to make this pipeline more generic and powerful I suggest the following:

1- This pipeline has a big restriction which is that it can only classify the traffic sign if it was only centered in the image, so if the image contained other different objects, the model wouldn't be able to recognize the sign firstly then classify it. Hence, this pipeline would be really powerful if it got attached to another which do all the recognition work first.
